This paper deals with analyzing the sensitivity of meta-level features and social dynamics on the popularity of YouTube videos. The analysis involves examining real-world data consisting of millions of videos and channels. The paper's focus on user engagement, video optimization, and social dynamics suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories. Specifically, it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with social dynamics and user engagement. It could also belong to cs.MM (Multimedia) as it deals with analyzing video content and optimizing video features. Additionally, it could belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as it deals with analyzing the impact of meta-level features on video popularity. The paper's focus on user engagement and understanding user behavior suggests that it could also belong to cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
